				<p><p>In addition to Mindstorms being a good start for software, there are competitions for younger students such as FIRST robotics, and <a href="http://www.botball.org/" rel="nofollow">Botball</a> where Legos plays a large role(may not be found everywhere though). You learn software, and also how to design a robot to perform a specific task or tasks. </p>

<p>However you will not learn the electronics side thus missing out on a huge part of the experience. While I haven't tested it, I started with a kit similar to this <a href="http://www.adafruit.com/product/749" rel="nofollow">Parallax BOEBot from Adafruit</a>. It serves as not only an introduction to software, but also the parts involved and assembly. The downside here is that you're not working with Legos and so the ability to reconfigure and build something new is lacking. </p>
